Date:  0/0/1874
Source:  NZ Sheepfarming
Author:  CAIRD
Vol / Page:  26
Edition:
Quote:  The words `terrace' and `flat', so often used, rather aptly describe the general nature of the country. A flat means a plain, but it is a rare thing to gallop along a flat for more than a mile without coming across a terrace, which terrace may be only six feet high, or it may be a hundred ... [and] is certain to be as regular as if it formed part of some ornamental ground.
